@page "/"
@rendermode InteractiveServer
@using SkiaSharp
@using SkiaSharp.Views.Blazor

<PageTitle>SkiaSharp Blazor Server Test</PageTitle>
<h1>SkiaSharp Server-Side Blazor Test</h1>
<SKCanvasView OnPaintSurface="OnPaintSurface" style="width:400px;height:300px;" />

@code {
    private void OnPaintSurface(SKPaintSurfaceEventArgs e)
    {
        var canvas = e.Surface.Canvas;
        canvas.Clear(SKColors.CornflowerBlue);
        using var paint = new SKPaint { Color = SKColors.White, TextSize = 32, IsAntialias = true };
        canvas.DrawText("Hello from SkiaSharp!", 50, 150, paint);
        Console.WriteLine($"SUCCESS: rendered {e.Info.Width}x{e.Info.Height}");
    }
}

proposedResponse.body:
Thanks for the suggestion! We investigated and can confirm that server-side Blazor rendering is not currently available in SkiaSharp.

**Investigation:**
- SkiaSharp.Views.Blazor (tested 2.88.9 and 3.119.2) is explicitly WASM-only: `[SupportedOSPlatform("browser")]` on all view types
- The package depends on `SkiaSharp.NativeAssets.WebAssembly` — no server-side native assets
- JS interop throws `NotSupportedException("SkiaSharp currently only works on Web Assembly.")` when used outside WASM
- No server-side rendering code, SignalR marshaling, or alternative pipeline exists in any version including main

Client-side Blazor WASM support was delivered via PR #1811 and works well. The remaining server-side feature request would require a fundamentally different architecture (e.g., server-side image rendering sent as encoded images, or SKPicture serialization over SignalR).

**Workaround for server-side scenarios today:** Use standard SkiaSharp on the server to render images, encode as PNG/JPEG, and send to the client as `<img>` tags:

```csharp
using var surface = SKSurface.Create(new SKImageInfo(width, height));
var canvas = surface.Canvas;
// ... draw operations ...
using var image = surface.Snapshot();
using var data = image.Encode(SKEncodedImageFormat.Png, 100);
var base64 = Convert.ToBase64String(data.ToArray());
// Render as <img src="data:image/png;base64,..." />
```

Keeping this open to track the server-side Blazor feature request.
